  <!-- ============ SECTION 1 — EXECUTIVE OVERVIEW ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>1.&nbsp; Executive Overview</h1>

  <h2>1.1&nbsp; What is AITAS?</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    <b>AITAS (AI Test Automation System)</b> is an enterprise platform that uses
    artificial intelligence to accelerate the entire software testing lifecycle &mdash;
    from authoring test cases, to generating executable automation scripts, to running
    them across web, mobile, API, and desktop targets, to healing broken tests and
    reporting results. It is purpose-built for <b>regulated healthcare environments</b>,
    where speed must never compromise traceability, control, or compliance.
  </p>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Rather than replacing engineers, AITAS amplifies them. AI drafts the first version of
    every artifact; qualified people review, refine, and approve it. The result is a
    dramatic reduction in manual effort while preserving the human accountability that
    regulated validation demands.
  </p>

  <h2>1.2&nbsp; The Problem It Solves</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><b>Slow authoring.</b> Manually writing test cases and scripts is the largest
        bottleneck in most QA organizations.</li>
    <li><b>Brittle automation.</b> UI changes break selectors and locators, forcing
        expensive maintenance cycles.</li>
    <li><b>Fragmented tooling.</b> Separate tools for web, mobile, API, and performance
        testing create silos and duplicate effort.</li>
    <li><b>Compliance overhead.</b> Regulated teams must evidence who did what, when, and
        why &mdash; for every change.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    AITAS addresses all four by unifying generation, execution, healing, and governance
    in a single, auditable platform.
  </p>

  <h2>1.3&nbsp; Business Value</h2>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:32%">Outcome</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Faster delivery</b></td><td>AI drafts test cases and scripts in seconds, compressing authoring time from days to minutes.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>Lower maintenance</b></td><td>The AI Self-Healing engine repairs broken selectors automatically, reducing flaky-test triage.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>One platform</b></td><td>Web, mobile, API, desktop, and performance testing are unified under one governance model.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>Audit confidence</b></td><td>Every action is recorded with user, timestamp, and rationale &mdash; ready for inspection.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Reusable knowledge</b></td><td>An organizational knowledge base feeds context to the AI so output improves over time.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>1.4&nbsp; Compliance Posture</h2>
  <table class=callout><tr><td class=c-success>
    <b>Designed for validation.</b>&nbsp; AITAS aligns to <b>21 CFR Part 11</b>
    (electronic records &amp; signatures), <b>GxP</b> good-practice expectations, and
    <b>SOX</b> change-control principles. Core enablers include human-in-the-loop
    approvals, role-based access control (RBAC), immutable audit logging, and explicit
    AI-assistance disclosure on every generated artifact.
  </td></tr></table>

  <h2>1.5&nbsp; Intended Audience</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><b>QA &amp; Automation Engineers</b> &mdash; generate, edit, execute, and heal tests.</li>
    <li><b>Test Leads &amp; Managers</b> &mdash; track coverage, review reports, govern approvals.</li>
    <li><b>Validation &amp; Compliance</b> &mdash; inspect the audit trail and compliance dashboards.</li>
    <li><b>Platform Administrators</b> &mdash; manage users, roles, agents, and environments.</li>
    <li><b>Stakeholders</b> &mdash; understand capability, value, and posture at a glance.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 2 — KEY FEATURES ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>2.&nbsp; Key Features &amp; Capabilities</h1>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    The following capabilities form the functional backbone of AITAS. Each is described
    operationally in Section&nbsp;5 (Module-by-Module Guide).
  </p>

  <h3>2.1&nbsp; AI Test Generation</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Describe a requirement in plain language &mdash; or upload a requirements
    document/spreadsheet &mdash; and AITAS drafts structured test cases with steps,
    expected results, and priority. It can then convert approved cases into executable
    automation scripts for your chosen framework.
  </p>

  <h3>2.2&nbsp; Governed, Human-in-the-Loop Workflow</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Nothing AI produces is trusted blindly. Generated artifacts enter a review state and
    must be approved by an authorized user before they are considered validated. The
    platform records the reviewer, decision, and timestamp.
  </p>

  <h3>2.3&nbsp; Multi-Platform Execution</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Run automation against <b>web</b> (Playwright/Selenium), <b>mobile</b>
    (Appium), <b>API</b> (HTTP-level), and <b>desktop</b> targets &mdash; locally or
    through distributed execution agents &mdash; with consolidated results.
  </p>

  <h3>2.4&nbsp; AI Self-Healing</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    When a UI change breaks a locator, the Self-Healing engine proposes a corrected
    selector using contextual cues, so suites stay green with minimal manual repair.
    Healing actions are logged and reviewable.
  </p>

  <h3>2.5&nbsp; Execution Agents (Local &amp; Enterprise)</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Lightweight agents let you execute tests on your own machines or on a managed grid.
    Enterprise agents support pooling, health monitoring, and scale-out for high-volume
    suites.
  </p>

  <h3>2.6&nbsp; Multi-Agent Orchestration</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Coordinate multiple specialized AI agents (e.g., generation, review, healing) to
    collaborate on complex testing tasks, with the platform mediating their hand-offs.
  </p>

  <h3>2.7&nbsp; Knowledge Base &amp; Retrieval</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    A searchable organizational knowledge base stores domain context, standards, and
    prior artifacts. Relevant knowledge is retrieved to ground AI output, improving
    accuracy and consistency.
  </p>

  <h3>2.8&nbsp; Coverage &amp; Reporting</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Visualize requirement-to-test coverage, pass/fail trends, execution history, and
    exportable reports for stakeholders and auditors.
  </p>

  <h3>2.9&nbsp; Performance &amp; Data Factory</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Generate load/performance scenarios and synthesize realistic, privacy-safe test data
    on demand to feed your test runs.
  </p>

  <h3>2.10&nbsp; CI/CD Integration, RBAC &amp; Audit</h3>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Trigger suites from pipelines, enforce role-based permissions, and rely on an
    immutable audit trail spanning generation, approval, execution, and healing.
  </p>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 3 — TECHNOLOGY STACK ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>3.&nbsp; Technology Stack</h1>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    AITAS is a modern full-stack TypeScript application. The same language spans client
    and server, simplifying maintenance and enabling shared types end-to-end.
  </p>

  <h2>3.1&nbsp; Frontend</h2>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:30%">Technology</th><th>Role</th></tr>
    <tr><td>React 18 + TypeScript</td><td>Component-based UI with full type safety.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>Vite</td><td>Lightning-fast dev server and optimized production builds.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Wouter</td><td>Lightweight client-side routing (see Appendix B route map).</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>Tailwind CSS</td><td>Utility-first styling with the Baxter design tokens.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>shadcn/ui + Radix UI</td><td>Accessible, composable component primitives.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>TanStack Query</td><td>Server-state management, caching, and data fetching.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Lucide Icons</td><td>Consistent iconography across the product.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>3.2&nbsp; Backend</h2>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:30%">Technology</th><th>Role</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Node.js + Express</td><td>HTTP API server and application orchestration.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>TypeScript</td><td>End-to-end type safety shared with the client.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Drizzle ORM</td><td>Type-safe database access and schema migrations.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>SQLite (dev) / SQL DB (prod)</td><td>Relational persistence for projects, tests, runs, and audit.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Session-based Auth</td><td>Secure login, password policy, and RBAC enforcement.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>3.3&nbsp; Test Execution Engines</h2>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:30%">Engine</th><th>Target</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Playwright</td><td>Modern cross-browser web automation.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>Selenium</td><td>Established web automation compatibility.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Appium</td><td>Native &amp; hybrid mobile automation.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>HTTP/API runners</td><td>Service-level and contract testing.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>3.4&nbsp; AI &amp; Knowledge</h2>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:30%">Component</th><th>Role</th></tr>
    <tr><td>LLM Integration</td><td>Drafts test cases, scripts, and healing suggestions.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>Vector Index</td><td>Semantic retrieval over the knowledge base for grounded generation.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Prompt &amp; Governance Layer</td><td>Standardizes generation and enforces review gating.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>3.5&nbsp; Operations</h2>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:30%">Tooling</th><th>Role</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Docker / docker-compose</td><td>Containerized, reproducible deployment.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>Execution Agents</td><td>Local and enterprise distributed test execution.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CI/CD Hooks</td><td>Pipeline-triggered test runs.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>Structured Logging</td><td>Operational visibility and troubleshooting.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 4 — ARCHITECTURE ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>4.&nbsp; System Architecture</h1>

  <h2>4.1&nbsp; High-Level View</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    AITAS follows a clean three-tier model: a React single-page application (client), an
    Express API (server), and a relational datastore &mdash; with AI services and
    execution engines attached as specialized subsystems.
  </p>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:26%">Layer</th><th>Responsibility</th></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Presentation</b></td><td>React SPA: navigation, forms, dashboards, editors, reporting.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>Application/API</b></td><td>Express routes: auth, generation, execution control, governance, audit.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>AI Services</b></td><td>LLM orchestration, prompt governance, vector retrieval, self-healing.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>Execution</b></td><td>Playwright/Selenium/Appium/API runners via local &amp; enterprise agents.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Data</b></td><td>Drizzle ORM over SQLite/SQL: projects, tests, runs, knowledge, audit.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>4.2&nbsp; Request &amp; Data Flow</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>The user acts in the React client (e.g., &ldquo;Generate test cases&rdquo;).</li>
    <li>TanStack Query calls the Express API with the authenticated session.</li>
    <li>The server invokes the AI service, grounded by knowledge-base retrieval.</li>
    <li>Draft artifacts are persisted in a <i>review</i> state via Drizzle ORM.</li>
    <li>An authorized user reviews and approves; the decision is audit-logged.</li>
    <li>Approved scripts are dispatched to execution agents; results stream back.</li>
    <li>Dashboards, coverage, and reports update from stored run data.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>4.3&nbsp; Authentication &amp; Authorization</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Access begins at a secure login. Sessions are server-managed; a password policy and
    forced-change flow protect first-use credentials. <b>Role-based access control</b>
    governs which modules and actions each user may perform (see Section&nbsp;8).
  </p>

  <h2>4.4&nbsp; Auditability by Design</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Generation, approval, execution, and healing each emit immutable audit entries
    capturing the actor, timestamp, and context. This trail is the foundation of the
    platform&rsquo;s 21 CFR Part 11 alignment.
  </p>

  <h2>4.5&nbsp; Project Structure (Source Layout)</h2>
  <table class=kv>
    <tr><td class=k>client/</td><td class=v>React SPA &mdash; pages, components, hooks, brand assets.</td></tr>
    <tr><td class=k>server/</td><td class=v>Express API &mdash; routes, AI services, execution control, auth.</td></tr>
    <tr><td class=k>shared/</td><td class=v>Types &amp; schema shared between client and server.</td></tr>
    <tr><td class=k>scripts/</td><td class=v>Utilities, seeders, and documentation generators.</td></tr>
    <tr><td class=k>docs/</td><td class=v>Project documentation (this file).</td></tr>
  </table>

