  <!-- ============ SECTION 6 — WORKFLOWS ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>6.&nbsp; End-to-End Workflows</h1>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    The following workflows tie the modules together into the way teams actually work.
  </p>

  <h2>6.1&nbsp; From Requirement to Approved Test Case</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Open <b>Test Generator</b> (<span class=mono>/generator</span>).</li>
    <li>Enter a clear requirement (or import via <b>Upload</b>).</li>
    <li>Click <b>Generate</b>; review the drafted steps and expected results.</li>
    <li>Edit as needed, then submit for approval.</li>
    <li>An authorized reviewer approves; the decision is audit-logged.</li>
    <li>The approved case appears in the <b>Repository</b>.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>6.2&nbsp; From Test Case to Executable Script</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Open an approved case and choose <b>Convert to Script</b>.</li>
    <li>Select the framework/target (web/mobile/API).</li>
    <li>Review the generated script in <b>Scripts</b> (<span class=mono>/scripts</span>).</li>
    <li>Adjust if required; the script links back to its source case.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>6.3&nbsp; Running &amp; Monitoring a Suite</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Ensure an <b>Agent</b> is online (see 5.8&ndash;5.10).</li>
    <li>Select an <b>Environment</b> (<span class=mono>/environments</span>).</li>
    <li>Launch from <b>Executions</b> (<span class=mono>/executions</span>).</li>
    <li>Watch live status; open a result for steps, logs, and artifacts.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>6.4&nbsp; Healing a Broken Test</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>A run fails due to a changed selector.</li>
    <li>Open <b>AI Self-Healing</b> (<span class=mono>/healer</span>).</li>
    <li>Review the proposed corrected selector; accept or reject.</li>
    <li>Re-run; the heal is recorded in history.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>6.5&nbsp; Reporting &amp; Audit</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Use <b>Coverage</b> (<span class=mono>/coverage</span>) to confirm requirement coverage.</li>
    <li>Generate a summary in <b>Reports</b> (<span class=mono>/reports</span>).</li>
    <li>Inspect the trail in <b>Compliance</b> (<span class=mono>/compliance</span>) and export evidence.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>6.6&nbsp; Continuous Testing in CI/CD</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Configure triggers in <b>CI/CD</b> (<span class=mono>/cicd</span>).</li>
    <li>Map suites to pipeline stages.</li>
    <li>On each build/deploy, suites run automatically and results flow back to AITAS.</li>
  </ol>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 7 — TESTING & VALIDATION ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>7.&nbsp; Testing &amp; Validation</h1>

  <h2>7.1&nbsp; How to Test the Platform Itself</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    To validate an AITAS deployment end-to-end, walk the following smoke path. It
    exercises authentication, generation, governance, execution, and reporting.
  </p>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:8%">Step</th><th>Action</th><th style="width:34%">Expected Result</th></tr>
    <tr><td>1</td><td>Sign in with valid credentials.</td><td>Dashboard loads; metrics render.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>2</td><td>Generate a test case from a sample requirement.</td><td>A structured draft with steps appears.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3</td><td>Approve the draft.</td><td>Status changes; audit entry recorded.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>4</td><td>Convert to a script.</td><td>Script generated and linked to the case.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>5</td><td>Bring an agent online and run it.</td><td>Execution completes; result visible.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>6</td><td>Trigger a heal on a deliberately broken selector.</td><td>A correction is proposed.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>7</td><td>Open Coverage and Reports.</td><td>Coverage maps; report exports.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td>8</td><td>Open Compliance.</td><td>Audit entries for the above are present.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>7.2&nbsp; Tips for Reliable Results</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Write specific requirements &mdash; ambiguity reduces generation quality.</li>
    <li>Keep the Knowledge Base current so AI output stays grounded.</li>
    <li>Confirm the target Environment and Agent before launching runs.</li>
    <li>Always review AI output before approval &mdash; this is required by design.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>7.3&nbsp; Building &amp; Running the Application</h2>
  <table class=kv>
    <tr><td class=k>Install</td><td class=v><span class=mono>npm install</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td class=k>Develop</td><td class=v><span class=mono>npm run dev</span> &mdash; starts the dev server (default port 5000).</td></tr>
    <tr><td class=k>Build</td><td class=v><span class=mono>npm run build</span> &mdash; produces optimized client + server bundles.</td></tr>
    <tr><td class=k>Containers</td><td class=v><span class=mono>docker-compose up</span> &mdash; reproducible deployment.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 8 — SECURITY & COMPLIANCE ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>8.&nbsp; Security &amp; Compliance</h1>

  <h2>8.1&nbsp; Authentication &amp; Access Control</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Secure, session-based login with a password policy.</li>
    <li>Forced password change on first use / reset.</li>
    <li><b>Role-based access control (RBAC)</b> gates modules and actions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>8.2&nbsp; Human-in-the-Loop Governance</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    AI is an accelerator, not an authority. Every generated artifact requires explicit
    human review and approval before it is treated as validated, ensuring accountable
    decision-making.
  </p>

  <h2>8.3&nbsp; Audit Trail</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Generation, approval, execution, and healing are recorded with actor, timestamp, and
    context. The trail is designed to be inspection-ready.
  </p>

  <h2>8.4&nbsp; Regulatory Alignment</h2>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:26%">Standard</th><th>How AITAS Supports It</th></tr>
    <tr><td><b>21 CFR Part 11</b></td><td>Electronic records &amp; signatures: unique users, approvals, immutable audit, AI-assistance disclosure.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>GxP</b></td><td>Good-practice controls: documented workflows, traceability, reviewer accountability.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>SOX</b></td><td>Change-control discipline: who changed what, when, and with what approval.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <table class=callout><tr><td class=c-warn>
    <b>Validation note.</b>&nbsp; AITAS provides the <i>controls and evidence</i> that
    support compliance. Formal validation (IQ/OQ/PQ) and qualification remain the
    responsibility of the deploying organization per its quality system.
  </td></tr></table>

  <!-- ============ SECTION 9 — OPERATIONS ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>9.&nbsp; Operations &amp; Maintenance</h1>

  <h2>9.1&nbsp; Deployment</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    AITAS ships with Docker support for reproducible deployment. Use environment
    configuration for database connections, secrets, and integration endpoints.
  </p>

  <h2>9.2&nbsp; Agents</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Keep at least one agent online for execution. For scale, use Enterprise Agents to
    pool capacity and monitor health.
  </p>

  <h2>9.3&nbsp; Backups &amp; Data</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Back up the application database (projects, tests, runs, knowledge, audit).</li>
    <li>Protect the audit store &mdash; it is your compliance evidence.</li>
    <li>Preserve the vector index for consistent knowledge retrieval.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>9.4&nbsp; Monitoring &amp; Logs</h2>
  <p class=MsoNormal>
    Structured logs provide operational visibility. Monitor agent health, execution
    throughput, and error rates; alert on anomalies.
  </p>

  <h2>9.5&nbsp; Routine Maintenance</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep dependencies and execution engines patched.</li>
    <li>Curate the Knowledge Base to sustain generation quality.</li>
    <li>Periodically review RBAC assignments for least privilege.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ============ APPENDICES ============ -->
  <div class=pagebreak></div>
  <h1>Appendix A&nbsp; &mdash; Glossary</h1>
  <table class=brand>
    <tr><th style="width:26%">Term</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
    <tr><td><b>AITAS</b></td><td>AI Test Automation System &mdash; this platform.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>Agent</b></td><td>A runner that executes tests on a target machine (local or enterprise grid).</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Artifact</b></td><td>Any generated item: a test case, a script, or a heal suggestion.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>Healing</b></td><td>Automatic repair of broken selectors/locators after UI change.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Human-in-the-loop</b></td><td>A workflow requiring human review/approval of AI output.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>Knowledge Base</b></td><td>Curated organizational context used to ground AI generation.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>RBAC</b></td><td>Role-Based Access Control.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>Vector Index</b></td><td>Semantic search structure enabling relevant knowledge retrieval.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>21 CFR Part 11</b></td><td>FDA regulation governing electronic records and signatures.</td></tr>
    <tr class=alt><td><b>GxP</b></td><td>Collective &ldquo;good practice&rdquo; quality guidelines in regulated industries.</td></tr>
  </table>

